            "title": "Taiwan lifts restrictions on food imports from Japan, Japanese government says",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>TOKYO (Reuters) -Taiwan has lifted all restrictions on food imports from Japan that were introduced after the Fukushima nuclear disaster in 2011, the Japanese government said on Friday.</p><p></p><p> (Reporting by Kiyoshi Takenaka and Anton BridgeEditing by David Goodman)</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/taiwan-lifts-restrictions-on-food-imports-from-japan-japanese-government-says-ce7d5edfdb88f32d",
            "pub_date": "2025-11-21 18:36:01",
            "source": "marketscreener",
            "kind": 1,
            "language": "en"
        },
        {
            "title": "Unilever considering sale of Marmite, Colman's brands - Reuters",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>(Alliance News) - Unilever PLC is considering the sale of several iconic British food brands, including Marmite yeast spread, Colman's mustard and Bovril beef extract, Reuters reported late Thursday, citing \"three people with knowledge of the matter\".</p><p></p><p>The London-based consumer goods maker is in the midst of a restructuring, including the demerger of Magnum Ice Cream Co NV into a separately listed company, scheduled for early next month. It has sold other food businesses as well in order to focus on beauty and wellbeing</p><!-- Article --><p></p><p>Reuters said two of the people said Unilever will keep the Pot Noodle brand.</p><p></p><p>One person told Reuters the British food brands being considered for sale have annual revenue of GBP200 million.</p><p></p><p>The news agency said Unilever declined to comment.</p><p></p><p>Unilever shares were up 1.4% to 4,546.00 pence on Friday morning.</p><p></p><p>By Tom Waite, Alliance News editor</p><p></p><p>Comments and questions to newsroom@alliancenews.com</p><p></p><p>Copyright 2025 Alliance News Ltd. All Rights Reserved.</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/unilever-considering-sale-of-marmite-colman-s-brands-reuters-ce7d5edfdb88f620",
            "pub_date": "2025-11-21 18:30:49",
            "source": "marketscreener",
            "kind": 1,
            "language": "en"
        },
        {
            "title": "Lithium prices plunge in China after moves to curb speculative trading",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>SHANGHAI (Reuters) -Lithium prices in China fell sharply on Friday, short-circuiting a rally, after the main exchange stepped in to curb speculative trading and on a report that battery giant CATL could restart production at its flagship lithium mine.</p><p>\n              The most-active lithium carbonate contract on the Guangzhou Futures Exchange closed daytime trading down 9% at 91,020 yuan  ($12,804.21) per metric ton, hitting its lower limit and giving back most of this week's gains.</p><!-- Article --><p>\n              The contract on Thursday hit its highest since June 2024 at 102,500 yuan a ton. </p><p>\n              On Thursday, GFEX said it would increase transaction fees for some futures contracts of lithium carbonate from November 24, and it also planned to limit the daily open position for non-futures company members.</p><p>\n              Such a move was widely seen as targeting speculative trading, analysts said, blaming some of the price correction on the decision.</p><p>\n              Bloomberg News reported on Friday that CATL is planning to restart production at its lithium mine in Yichun, Jiangxi Province. </p><p>\n              The Jianxiawo mine, where production has been suspended since August due to the expiration of its mining licence, can produce just over 46,000 tons of lithium carbonate equivalent a year, about 3% of global output for 2025, according to data from the Australian government.</p><p>\n              CATL has told its lithium carbonate smelters to be prepared for a resumption of the Jianxiawo mine, two sources told Reuters without specifying a date. </p><p>\n              The sources requested anonymity as they are not authorised to speak to the media.</p><p>\n              CATL did not respond to a request for comment. </p><p>\n              ($1 = 7.1086 Chinese yuan renminbi)</p><p></p><p> (Reporting by Dylan Duan and Lewis Jackson; Editing by Kirsten Donovan)</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/lithium-prices-plunge-in-china-after-moves-to-curb-speculative-trading-ce7d5edfdb88f722",
            "pub_date": "2025-11-21 18:30:50",
            "source": "marketscreener",
            "kind": 1,
            "language": "en"
        }
    ]
